				\begin{document}$$ accessibility(sub, res, con) $$\end{document} that returns true when access is granted. Then, we add a constraint that holds if the request for the given context is accessible and we ask Z3 to solve it. In contrast to [2], where two formulas are used, we use a single formula to compute both.

In this paper we compared Z3 with the B and Alloy models of SGAC [2] for checking SGAC properties. Our experiment shows that ProB is still the most adequate of the three solvers for this task. It is quite easy to use staged model finding in B to increase performance, compared to Z3 and Alloy. B operations can be easily used to compute the state variables needed to check the properties. During the development of the Z3 model, improvements were made to better take into account rule conditions. We were able to add constraints to the contexts, representing the formula of rule conditions. These modifications were also deployed on the B model. In future work, we plan to investigate the use of Z3 to further analyse rule conditions when a policy is constructed. Another approach would be to explore \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
